# Code style

## TypeScript

- Use **script mode** only (no `import type`-only files that require `module`). Prefer `satisfies` and inline types where it keeps code clear.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes; use `type` for unions, mapped types, and aliases.
- Use `const` by default; `let` only when reassignment is needed. No `var`.

## React components

- **Functional components only.** Define as `function ComponentName(props: Props)` or `const ComponentName = (props: Props) => { ... }`.
- **Named exports only** for components, hooks, and utilities. Use named exports in the defining file and named imports at the call site.
- **Exception:** Use **default export only for Next.js pages** (files in `app/**/page.tsx` or `pages/**/*.tsx`). All other modules use named exports.

```tsx
// ✅ Component file — named export
export function MatchCard({ match }: MatchCardProps) {
  return <article>...</article>;
}

// ✅ Page file — default export allowed
export default function LibraryPage() {
  return <div>...</div>;
}

// ❌ Non-page default export
export default function MatchCard() { ... }
```

## Styling

- Use **Tailwind CSS** for all styling. No CSS modules, styled-components, or inline style objects for layout/colors/spacing.
- Use Tailwind utility classes only. For repeated combinations, use `@apply` in a single shared CSS file only when the same 4+ utilities repeat in many places; otherwise keep utilities in JSX.
- Prefer Tailwind theme values (e.g. `text-primary`, `bg-background`) if the project defines them; otherwise use standard Tailwind tokens.

## File layout

- One primary component or hook per file. Co-locate small, single-use subcomponents in the same file if they are not reused elsewhere.
- Put types/interfaces in the same file as the component or in a shared `types` file; avoid scattering one-off types across many files.
